BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-ID:tufts_tdps
X-SOURCE:Tufts Tdps
SUMMARY:Rehearsal as Research: “Japanese Tea Ceremony” in Practice and i
 n Performance
LOCATION:Medford/Somerville campus
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260409T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260409T133000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Tufts Event Tem
 plate
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Building";ID=23241;TYPE=CustomAsset:Aidekman 
 Arts Center
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="City";ID=23311;TYPE=CustomAsset:Medford\, MA 
 02155
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Thumbnail";ID=23257;TYPE=Image:https://www.tr
 umba.com/i/DgDjW03zmzxYIJCCjADFYRkg.jpg
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Campus";ID=40542;TYPE=CustomAsset:Medford/Som
 erville campus
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Location Details";ID=23341;TYPE=MultiLine:Alu
 mnae Lounge
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Open to Public";ID=50013;TYPE=Boolean:Yes
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Subject";ID=67059;TYPE=CustomAsset:Thea
 ter/Dance
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Sponsor";ID=23731;TYPE=CustomAsset:Scho
 ol of Arts and Sciences
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgA4NF21ndZy%2AN8zbmsoFuH3.jpg
DTSTAMP:20260319T113255Z
DESCRIPTION:Building: Aidekman Arts Center\nCity: Medford\, MA 02155\nCa
 mpus: Medford/Somerville campus\nLocation Details: Alumnae Lounge\nOpen 
 to Public: Yes\nEvent Subject: Theater/Dance\nEvent Sponsor: School of A
 rts and Sciences\n\nRehearsal as Research: “Japanese Tea Ceremony” in Pr
 actice and in Performance\nIn contemporary Japanese Tea (chanoyu\, chado
 \, or “Japanese tea ceremony”)\, practitioners learn to distinguish betw
 een “practice” in the sense of rehearsal\, as carried out in weekly recu
 rring sessions with an instructor versus what is often called “real tea
 \,” corresponding to the sense of performance\, the public culmination of
  rehearsal. Despite the seeming primacy of the “real” Performance\, most
  practitioners end up spending the vast majority of the time they spent 
 doing tea in rehearsal\, not in performance. Of course\, such a divide i
 s also fundamental to theater practice as well\, and paying more attenti
 on to what is learned in each format and where scholars derive their kno
 wledge of the whole practice may open new insights into where and how pe
 rformative norms like “identity” and “culture” are maintained\, perpetua
 ted\, and evolve.\n\nMichelle Liu Carriger\, PhD has been studying the U
 rasenke tradition of chado (“tea ceremony”) since 1999\, in various loca
 tions including Los Angeles\, Colorado\, Kansas\, Boston\, London\, and 
 in Kyoto during a yearlong Midorikai fellowship at the Urasenke Gakuen P
 rofessional College of Chado. She holds a second degree Urasenke teachin
 g license and chamei (tea name) “Somi.” Additionally\, she researches an
 d writes academically on tea practice and theory and spent two years in 
 rural Ehime prefecture\, Japan\, studying in the Omotesenke lineage.
CATEGORIES:Theatre, Dance, and Performance Studies
