 ol of Arts and Sciences
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Contact Name";ID=23336;TYPE=SingleLine:
 John Stark
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Contact Email";ID=23314;TYPE=Email:John
 .Stark@tufts.edu
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event image";ID=40;TYPE=Image:https://www.tru
 mba.com/i/DgAAtVCzflIuhu-3MwusFKeF.jpg
DTSTAMP:20260325T101407Z
DESCRIPTION:Building: Aidekman Arts Center\nCity: Medford\, MA 02155\nRo
 om: Balch Arena Theater\nCampus: Medford/Somerville campus\nOpen to Publ
 ic: Yes\nEvent Type: Performance\nEvent Subject: Theater/Dance\nEvent Sp
 onsor: School of Arts and Sciences\nEvent Contact Name: John Stark\nEven
 t Contact Email: John.Stark@tufts.edu\nLink: https://www.tuftstdpsticket
 s.com/section/tdps-2025-2026-season-ywz8\n\nTICKETS ON SALE NOW: \nhttps
 ://www.tuftstdpstickets.com/\n\nWritten by Terayama Shūji\, in collabora
 tion with Kishida Rio\nTranslated by Tsuneda Keiko and Colleen Lanki\nDi
 rected by August Kittleson as part of a senior thesis project in Theatre
 \, Dance\, and Performance studies\n\nPlease join us after this performa
 nce for a celebratory opening night reception.\n\nTerayama Shuji’s 1975 
 play\, A Journal of the Plague Year\, pushes us to think about the viole
 nce of a nation’s imperial past (or present!) and epidemic disease both 
 as a literal threat and as a metaphor for the way war crimes infect vict
 ims and perpetrators alike.\n\nIt can also be seen as a play about prote
 st\, resistance\, and activism. Its emphasis on memory\, for instance\, 
 as an act of resistance against colonial amnesia\, and community in the 
 face of all that tears us apart\, is profoundly relevant for a 21st-cent
 ury US-based audience. \n\nThe message of hopeful urgency at the end of 
 the play—“The time is now! The time is now!”—captures the spirit of stud
 ent protest today.
CATEGORIES:Theatre, Dance, and Performance Studies
